#AFTER CONNECTING TO EC2 VIA SSH
->

Next Steps: Setting Up CloudWatch Monitoring
Since you want CloudOptiGuard to optimize and monitor cloud workloads, let's start by:

Download the CloudWatch Agent
Run this command to download the installer:
->cd /tmp
curl -O https://amazoncloudwatch-agent.s3.amazonaws.com/amazon_linux/amd64/latest/amazon-cloudwatch-agent.rpm

Install the Agent
->sudo rpm -Uvh amazon-cloudwatch-agent.rpm

Verify the Installation
Check if the agent was installed successfully:
->amazon-cloudwatch-agent --version


✅ 1. Updating the system:
->sudo yum update -y

✅ 2. Installing the CloudWatch Agent:
->sudo yum install -y amazon-cloudwatch-agent

✅ 3. Checking the CloudWatch Agent version (to verify installation):
->amazon-cloudwatch-agent --version

✅ 4. Setting up the CloudWatch Agent:
Run this command to start the CloudWatch agent configuration wizard:
->sudo amazon-cloudwatch-agent-config-wizard
Answer the questions to configure the metrics and logs you want to monitor.

->amazon-cloudwatch-agent --version


#Configure CloudWatch Agent
Run the configuration wizard:
->sudo amazon-cloudwatch-agent-config-wizard
This will guide you through setting up metrics and logs for monitoring.

#Start the CloudWatch Agent
Once configured, start the agent using:
->sudo systemctl start amazon-cloudwatch-agent

#To check the status:
->sudo systemctl status amazon-cloudwatch-agent
If it’s active (running), you’re good to go. ✅

#Enable CloudWatch Agent on Boot
To ensure it starts automatically with the server:
->sudo systemctl enable amazon-cloudwatch-agent
